1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:08,950
Learn ML molecular dynamics by building it — from F=ma to foundation models.

2
00:00:08,950 --> 00:00:16,300
Molecular dynamics is just F=ma in a loop. The only hard part is knowing the force.

3
00:00:16,300 --> 00:00:26,210
Classical writes the force by hand — fine for argon, broken for real chemistry. AI learns it from data.

4
00:00:26,210 --> 00:00:34,090
An MD engine in ~60 lines of NumPy — atoms move…

5
00:00:34,090 --> 00:00:40,100
…and total energy stays flat — the first sign the simulation is honest.

6
00:00:40,100 --> 00:00:50,280
Lennard-Jones can't tune bond strength, and its tail is the wrong physics for a real bond.

7
00:00:50,280 --> 00:00:59,500
Energy becomes a neural network — and the forces come free from autograd.

8
00:00:59,500 --> 00:01:08,040
Rotate the system or reorder the atoms — the energy must not change. That constraint IS the design.

9
00:01:08,040 --> 00:01:15,410
Modern potentials are geometry-aware graph neural networks.

10
00:01:15,410 --> 00:01:31,810
Load MACE-MP (trained on ~160,000 DFT calcs) and simulate water zero-shot: O–H bond 0.97 Å, close to experiment.

11
00:01:31,810 --> 00:01:44,430
A learned potential can fail silently out of distribution — the trajectory looks fine but the physics is wrong. Committee uncertainty catches it.

12
00:01:44,430 --> 00:01:54,660
Periodic boundaries give a surface-free bulk liquid — no evaporation, fixed density.

13
00:01:54,660 --> 00:02:06,790
The RDF settles to 1 at large r — the signature of a real bulk liquid — and we read off a diffusion coefficient (reduced units).

14
00:02:06,790 --> 00:02:15,180
The physics is tested, not asserted: forces match the gradient of the energy, and energy stays conserved.

15
00:02:15,180 --> 00:02:24,320
Eight runnable notebooks · a tested NumPy engine · MIT · github.com/spacegiyou/atoms-from-scratch

